				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R$$\end{document} jet trigger, as shown in Fig. 24b. The performance of the jet trigger in the simulation is seen to be broadly in agreement with data for the large-R\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R$$\end{document} jet trigger where the larger jet width selection exhibits a sharper rising edge. The rising edge is considerably less sharp for the standard jet trigger and shows significantly more variability with the properties of the sample. The large-R\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R$$\end{document} jet trigger is therefore more robust to changes of the jet width, which is a measure of jet substructure and radiation profiles.

The single inclusive jet triggers with R=0.4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R=0.4$$\end{document} have a sharply rising edge for jets with a narrow energy core, but the performance is reduced for jets with wider, or multi-pronged energy distributions. Jet triggers with large-R\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R$$\end{document} not only improve the performance for jets with wide energy distributions but also improve the performance for jets with a narrow energy core although at the cost of greatly increasing both the sensitivity of the trigger to pile-up, and the trigger rate.

The dominant issue for jet measurements in the HI environment is the presence of a large amount of additional energy coming from the underlying event (UE), additional interactions originating from the same Pb+Pb collision. The properties of this energy depend on the impact parameter, or minimum transverse distance between the two colliding nuclei. A direct measurement of the impact parameter is not possible and so the centrality of the collision, defined as the ET\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_\mathrm{T}$$\end{document} deposited in forward calorimeter, FCal ΣET\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Sigma E_{\mathrm {T}}$$\end{document}, is used to characterise the UE [52]. The distribution of FCal ΣET\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Sigma E_{\mathrm {T}}$$\end{document} is shown in Fig. 25 and is divided into bins according to percentiles of the total Pb+Pb cross section.Fig. 25
The distribution of the transverse energy deposited in forward calorimeter, FCal ΣET\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
