During the first LHC Pb+Pb run, in 2010, all events identified by the minimum bias (MB) and forward detector triggers [3, 13] were recorded and used for the HI studies. However, in 2011 the instantaneous luminosity substantially increased, such that the peak rate of MB L1 triggers exceeded 6 kHz. Therefore to maintain efficiency for events containing high pT\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p_{\text {T}}$$\end{document} jets, MB events identified at L1 were passed through L2 to the EF where specialised HI jet triggers were used to select events.

The L1 MB triggers based on the total summed transverse energy in the calorimeter were used as the L1 seeds for HLT triggers which reconstruct high pT\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p_{\text {T}}$$\end{document} electrons, muons and jets. Events were transferred directly to the EF if the total transverse energy deposited in the calorimeters exceeded 10 GeV. A detailed description of the performance of various MB triggers in HI collisions can be found elsewhere [54].

