The heavy ion programme at the LHC will provide crucial information about the formation of a hot evanescent medium at the highest temperatures and densities ever created in the laboratory. The ATLAS jet trigger algorithm performs well in the HI environment, using the same anti-kt\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$k_{t}$$\end{document} algorithm used for pp physics. A small efficiency degradation with increasing centrality is observed, which is less pronounced for smaller radius parameters. The angular resolution is good, but shows some centrality dependence for larger radius parameters.

The ATLAS jet trigger has been designed to provide an online reconstruction of jets matching as closely as possible those from the offline reconstruction. For this reason, while the RoI approach is mandatory for reasons of bandwidth limitation at L1 and L2, during Run 1 the jet trigger for the EF processed events using the full calorimeter data and using the same anti-kt\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$k_{t}$$\end{document} algorithm as used offline.

For unbiased trigger selection of jets with lower ET\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_\mathrm{T}$$\end{document}, chains seeded by a random trigger at L1 with a large prescale and passing through L2 – so not requiring a jet seed at either L1 or L2 – were deployed. After accounting for the large prescale, these randomly seeded EF triggers were fully efficient for jets with offline ET\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_\mathrm{T}$$\end{document} greater then 25 GeV.

For offline jets with ET>60\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_\mathrm{T}>60$$\end{document} GeV the jets are reconstructed at the EF in the barrel region with a resolution in ET\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_\mathrm{T}$$\end{document} with respect to offline jets, of better than 4 % and better than 2.5 % in the endcaps. The performance in terms of offset and resolution of the jet trigger in data is reasonably well modelled by the Monte Carlo detector simulation to better than 1 %, but slightly worse in the crack regions between the barrel and endcap calorimeters. However, the steeply falling jet pT\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p_{\text {T}}$$\end{document} spectrum means that small differences in the offset between data and the simulation results in differences in the positions of the rising edges of the jet trigger when comparing simulation with data. Physics analyses typically use data only for which the appropriate jet trigger has reached maximal efficiency in order to ameliorate the effect of these differences.

